{"type":"text","timestamp":1777219238206,"sessionID":"ses_2357b14d7ffeOE6IVwCwGTxoqm","part":{"id":"prt_dca854414001jN38xD6MiWsVDT","messageID":"msg_dca85138e001QsC2jFnxIX97RC","sessionID":"ses_2357b14d7ffeOE6IVwCwGTxoqm","type":"text","text":"Ablation analysis across the five dimensions:\n\n**Consistency** — CRUD wins. Standard ACID transactions give you immediate strong consistency per-order. Event sourcing is *eventually* consistent by design (read-side projections lag behind writes). For order management — where double-booking or stale inventory reads lose money — this matters. **Verdict: CRUD.**\n\n**Query performance** — CRUD wins. A simple `SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = ?` with indexes is sub-millisecond. Event sourcing requires replaying the event stream or maintaining projections, and any ad-hoc query (e.g., \"orders by region, status, and payment method\") means building curated materialized views. **Verdict: CRUD.**\n\n**Learning curve** — CRUD wins by a mile. Any developer can build CRUD endpoints in an afternoon. Event sourcing demands understanding aggregates, event stores, projections, sagas/process managers, CQRS, event versioning, and snapshotting — a 3-6 month ramp for a team new to it. **Verdict: CRUD.**\n\n**Scalability** — Event sourcing wins. Append-only event store with no update contention; natural sharding by aggregate ID on writes; unlimited read replicas via projections. CRUD has write contention on shared rows and scaling writes horizontally is notoriously painful (distributed transactions, 2PC). **Verdict: Event Sourcing.**\n\n**Ops cost** — CRUD wins significantly. Event sourcing means running and maintaining an event store (Kafka/EventStoreDB), debugging eventual consistency issues, rebuilding projections after schema changes, handling event schema evolution, and snapshot management. CRUD: any Postgres/MySQL instance, done. **Verdict: CRUD.**\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation: CRUD** — with high confidence.\n\nEvent sourcing only earns back its costs at massive scale (millions of events/sec) or when you *need* the full audit trail as a hard business requirement (finance, compliance). For a typical order management system, CRUD is simpler, faster to build, cheaper to run, and easier to hire for. You can always add a simple ordered-domain-events table on the side if you want async projections later — event sourcing-lite without the full burden.","time":{"start":1777219238205,"end":1777219238205}}}
